# Learning experience for focused concept

## Developed Level Throughout the Course

At the beginning of the course, we knew almost nothing about BIM—not even the basic principles—and we were unfamiliar with IfcOpenShell. We had some experience with Python, but we had never used GitHub before. During the first assignments, we struggled quite a bit with the whole GitHub process and lost some time getting used to it. As the assignments progressed, we gained more insight into how to use GitHub and how to understand the model through the code. We also started to see the value and purpose of BIM.

Because we already had a broad architectural background, Assignment 2 (creating the flowchart) went more smoothly. This task required us to understand the building itself and define the principles of our chosen topic within the focus area. Translating this understanding into code for A3 and A4, and then analyzing that code to interpret the model and identify potential errors, was more challenging. However, we eventually learned how to properly analyze a model and gained a much better understanding of the code. The most important lesson we learned is that many imperfections can exist within a model, and these can significantly influence the BIM analysis.

## Other Things We Still Need to Learn

One thing we still need to learn more about is the role of the manager. Understanding this would help us better grasp how the work of the analysts is combined, as well as the challenges that come with this process. As analysts, this would allow us to better anticipate these issues and ensure smoother interaction between the different roles. The separate pieces of code would then become clearer and more easily form a coherent whole.

## OpenBIM in the Future

OpenBIM is definitely something we would use again, especially to check a design—particularly in the early stages—for errors and to optimize it as soon as possible. This helps avoid the high costs associated with changes made later in the design process.

## Process of developing the tutorial

### Did the process of the course enable you to answer or define questions that you might need later for your thesis?

Yes. The course helped us formulate potential research questions. While examining the IFC model, we encountered numerous inconsistencies and errors, especially regarding naming conventions and other parameters that differed across models. This highlighted the need for a more generalised approach to model checking—one that works across various models without depending on specific naming structures. Such an approach could greatly increase the efficiency of the checking process and forms a strong basis for a potential thesis topic.

### Would you have preferred to have been given less choice in the use cases?

No, this was not an issue for us. The large variety of options was actually positive, and we chose topics that align closely with our background in architecture. Circulation routes, for example, are a central part of building design, and we had already explored these thoroughly in earlier design projects in Belgium. Therefore, the level of freedom in choosing a use case was appropriate.

### Was the number of tools for the course ok - should we have more or less? If so which ones would you leave out?

Although the course introduced many different tools, they generally worked well together and aligned with the assignments. That said, being confronted with so many tools at the start can be quite overwhelming, but at the end we felt it was the right amount.

## Summary of feedback on tutorial from others

The tutorial was clearly explained, and the tool fulfilled its intended purpose: checking the fire evacuation routes. It was also appreciated that we visualised the Excel results directly in the model, creating a clear physical translation.

However, our tool turned out to be quite specific. A more general tool—for example one that checks the overall fire safety of the building, including additional elements such as façade components—could make it more widely applicable. It would also help if the tool were less dependent on object naming conventions, since the current version requires the model to follow certain naming rules to function correctly.

Another point raised by the manager was that the analysts all submitted documents in different formats. This made it difficult and inefficient to work with. It would be more effective if all analysts agreed beforehand on which formats they would use.

We received feedback as well that our coding tutorial could function not only for people who make a code but also as guidance for modellers. The code outputs revealed several modelling issues, indirectly demonstrating how models should be structured and where common mistakes occur. As a result, the tutorial not only explains the code but also helps users understand how to create more consistent and accurate models. This was considered a valuable added benefit.

Lastly, we used bounding boxes to determine object dimensions when these were not provided. Caution is needed here: in models where elements are rotated and not orthogonally aligned, bounding boxes may not rotate with the object (see figure below). This can lead to incorrect dimensions because the bounding box does not follow the actual shape of the element. In our model this was not an issue, as the objects were not rotated.

